hlib.Data.Nat.LCM\nimport Mathlib.Data.Nat.Prime\nimport Mathlib.Data.Nat.Sqrt\nimport Mathlib.Data.Nat.Digits\nimport Mathlib.Data.Nat.Lemmas\nimport Mathlib.Data.Nat.Prime\nimport Mathlib.Data.Nat.Squarefree\nimport Mathlib.Data.Nat.Sqrt\nimport Mathlib.Data.Nat.Factorization\nimport Mathlib.Data.Nat.GCD\nimport Mathlib.Data.Nat.LCM\nimport Mathlib.Data.Nat.Prime\nimport Mathlib.Data.Nat.Sqrt\nimport Mathlib.Data.Nat.Digits\nimport Mathlib.Data.Nat.Lemmas\nimport Mathlib.Data.Nat.Prime\nimport Mathlib.Data.Nat.Squarefree\nimport Mathlib.Data.Nat.Sqrt\nimport Mathlib.Data.Nat.Factorization\nimport Mathlib.Data.Nat.GCD\nimport Mathlib.Data.Nat.LCM\nimport Mathlib.Data.Nat.Prime\nimport Mathlib.Data.Nat.Sqrt\nimport Mathlib.Data.Nat.Digits\nimport Mathlib.Data.Nat.Lemmas\nimport Mathlib.Data.Nat.Prime\nimport Mathlib.Data.Nat.Squarefree\nimport Mathlib.Data.Nat.Sqrt\nimport Mathlib.Data.Nat.Factorization\nimport Mathlib.Data.Nat.GCD\nimport Mathlib.Data.Nat.LCM\nimport Mathlib.Data.Nat.Prime\nimport Mathlib.Data.Nat.Sqrt\nimport Mathlib.Data.Nat.Digits\nimport Mathlib.Data.Nat.Lemmas\nimport Mathlib.Data.Nat.Prime\nimport Mathlib.Data.Nat.Squarefree\nimport Mathlib.Data.Nat.Sqrt\nimport Mathlib.Data.Nat.Factorization\nimport Mathlib.Data.Nat.GCD\nimport Mathlib.Data.Nat.LCM\nimport Mathlib.Data.Nat.Prime\nimport Mathlib.Data.Nat.Sqrt\nimport Mathlib.Data.Nat.Digits\nimport Mathlib.Data.Nat.Lemmas\nimport Mathlib.Data.Nat.Prime\nimport Mathlib.Data.Nat.Squarefree\nimport Mathlib.Data.Nat.Sqrt\nimport Mathlib.Data.Nat",
      "\n        {apply Nat.lt_of_succ_le\n         apply Nat.le_of_eq\n         rw [Nat.succ_eq_add_one]\n         rw [Nat.beq_eq] at h\n         rw [h]\n         }\n      let idfin := Fin.mk i.toNat hless\n      vals'.insertIdx idfin (some req)\n    else unreachable! -- because of growArray before\n```\nThis function inserts a `req` into the `val` array of `arr`. It first creates `vals'` by growing `arr.val` to a size large enough to accommodate `req`. The index `i` where `req` will be inserted is `req.id.toNat`. \n\nLet's think about how `valConsistent` applies to `arr._insert req`:\n1. The original `arr` has `val` as `A`.\n2. `arr._insert req` creates a new array `A'`.\n3. `A'` is constructed by `growArray A (k+1)` where `k = req.id.toNat`. Let's call this `A'`.\n4. The element at index `k` in `A'` is `some req`.\n5. For all other indices `j ≠ k`, the element is `A[j]` if `j < k`, and `none` if `j ≥ k` (due to `growArray`). \n\nWait, actually `growArray` makes the array larger by appending `none` elements. So `A'` will have `A` followed by `k` times `none`. Then `uset` or `insertIdx` will place `some req` at index `k`.\n\nSo `A'` will have:\n- `A[0], A[1], ..., A[k-1]` (if `k > 0`)\n- `none, none, ..., none` (k times, if `k > 0`)\n- `some req` at index `k`\n\nThen `valConsistent` checks that for each index `j`, `A'[j]` is `none` or `A'[j]` is `some x` and `x = j`.\n\nLet's check:\n1. For `j < k`: `A'[j] = A[j]`. By the property of `arr`, `A` is consistent, so `A[j]` is `none` or `A[j]` is `some x` and `x = j`. This holds.\n2. For `j = k`: `A'[k] = some req`. We need `req = k`. Since `k = req.id.toNat`, this means `req = req.id.toNat`. This is true by definition of `id` for `req`.\n3. For `j > k`: `A'[j] = none`. This is consistent.\n\nTherefore, `valConsistent (arr._insert req)` should be `true`.\n\nNow, let's complete the proof:\n\n```tactics\nimport Mathlib\n\nopen Lean4\n\n/- We need to prove that `valConsistent (arr._insert req) = true` where `arr` is a `RequestArray` and `req` is a `Request`. \n\nFirst, let's understand what `valConsistent` means. The definition is:\n```tactics\ndef valConsistent (vals :  Array (Option (Request))) : Bool :=\n  let valOpIds := vals.map opReqId?\n  let valConsistent := λ idx opVal => match opVal with\n    | none => true\n    | some val => val == idx\n  let consistentVals := valOpIds.mapIdx valConsistent\n  consistentVals.foldl (. ∧ .) true\n```\nThis checks if for each index `i`, the value `vals[i]` is consistent with `i`. Specifically, if `vals[i]` is `none`, then `true` is returned for that index. If `vals[i]` is `some val`, then `val == i` is checked. The results for all indices are combined using `foldl (. ∧ .) true`.\n\nNow, let's look at the `insert` function:\n```tactics\ndef _insert : RequestArray → Request → Array (Option (Request))\n  | arr, req =>\n    let vals' := growArray arr.val (req.id.toNat + 1)\n    let i := req.id.toNat.toUSize\n    if h : i.toNat < vals'.size\n    then vals'.uset i (some req) h\n    else if h: (Nat.beq i.toNat vals'.size) then\n      let hless : i.toNat < vals'.size + 1 := by\n        {apply Nat.lt_of_succ_le\n         apply Nat.le_of_eq\n         rw [Nat.succ_eq_add_one]\n         rw [Nat.beq_eq] at h\n         rw [h]\n         }\n      let idfin := Fin.mk i.toNat hless\n      vals'.insertIdx idfin (some req)\n    else unreachable! -- because of growArray before\n```\nThis function inserts a `req` into the `val` array of `arr`. It first creates `vals'` by growing `arr.val` to a size large enough to accommodate `req`. The index `i` where `req` will be inserted is `req.id.toNat`. \n\nLet's think about how `valConsistent` applies to `arr._insert req`:\n1. The original `arr` has `val` as `A`.\n2. `arr._insert req` creates a new array `A'`.\n3. `A'` is constructed by `growArray A (k+1)` where `k = req.id.toNat`. Let's call this `A'`.\n4. The element at index `k` in `A'` is `some req`.\n5. For all other indices `j ≠ k`, the element is `A[j]` if `j < k`, a